text:
Recently, me and friends visited a highly acclaimed restaurant. Although we weren't entirely satisfied with the taste, we had a few points to address and were confused about the ingredients in the soup.

We didn't smell any pleasant aromas, and the flavor of the soup left us puzzled. We ordered the Á∫¢Êû£È±º, but it had a strong fishy taste, and we even found sand in the clams. The portion of rice was small, and what made us hesitate even more was the additional charge of RM1 per small packet of tissues. We believe that providing complimentary tissues is a basic service for a restaurant, especially one of such size.

We bravely tried their signature spicy dish, B-0.5, but the spiciness exceeded our expectations. It completely overshadowed the flavor of the soup and left us feeling overwhelmed by the fiery sensation, making it difficult to adapt.

Overall, we were not satisfied with our experience at this restaurant and have decided not to visit again. However, if you are interested in a slightly sour and spicy taste or enjoy spicy challenges, you may have a different opinion.

address: Lot P2.07.00, Level 2 Pavilion,Pavilion Kuala Lumpur Bukit Bintang Street, Bukit Bintang Kuala Lumpur, Bukit Bintang, 55100 Wilayah Persekutuan, Federal Territory of Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia
text:
Visited Caf√© Kitsun√© at Pavilion KL with high expectations, the place looks fantastic, stylish, and inviting, definitely a luxury caf√© vibe. Unfortunately, the experience was seriously let down by the food, particularly the cake.
We ordered two of their cakes, expecting something high-quality to match the ambiance and pricing. Instead, we was served the driest, roughest cakes we've ever tasted, especially disappointing for a caf√© located in a premium mall. It tasted stale, lacked moisture, and had a texture more fitting of something left out for days than a freshly made dessert.
For a brand with such a strong reputation and aesthetic appeal, this level of quality is simply unacceptable. It felt like all the attention went into the branding and decor, with none left for product quality. We genuinely expected more from such an upscale location.
If you‚Äôre coming here just for the photos and atmosphere, you‚Äôll probably enjoy it. But if you're looking for a good caf√© experience with delicious food to match the environment, this was a huge letdown. Hope they seriously rethink their menu and quality control.

name: Dewakan Restaurant
address: Level 48, Skyviews, Naza Tower @, Platinum Park, Persiaran KLCC, Kuala Lumpur City Centre, 50088 Kuala Lumpur, Federal Territory of Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia
text:
As a visitor to Malaysia, I was excited to explore some of the recommended dining options and decided to try this restaurant, which was featured on the Michelin Guide 2025. Unfortunately, my experience was somewhat disappointing.

The first dish I tried was the satay, but it was served cold and seemed to have been left waiting for quite some time. This affected both the taste and the texture, and the same applied to the fried items which also lacked freshness. Another beef dish I ordered turned out to be quite tough and difficult to enjoy.

At the end of the meal, the staff encouraged us to leave a positive review by presenting a QR code. At that moment, I finally understood how the restaurant managed to achieve such a high Google rating of 4.7.

The only fortunate part was that this was not my very first meal in Malaysia. Otherwise, it might have left me with a rather poor impression. As a traveler, I still felt it was a missed opportunity to enjoy the diverse food culture Malaysia is so well known for.

That said, I look forward to trying other restaurants during my stay, and I believe there are many other excellent choices in Malaysia that visitors would not want to miss.

name: Helipad Kuala Lumpur
address: 34 Menara KH, Jln Sultan Ismail, Bukit Bintang, 50450 Kuala Lumpur, Wilayah Persekutuan Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia
text:
We chose Helipad to celebrate our anniversary, expecting a special evening with a great view and atmosphere. While the location is undeniably nice and the servers were friendly and attentive, our experience was unfortunately ruined by the manager‚Äôs attitude.

We made a reservation in advance and specifically requested a sofa table by the edge to enjoy the view. The reservation was confirmed, but when we arrived, the manager led us to a small table in the center with no view. When I reminded him of our request, he dismissed it coldly, saying that couples weren‚Äôt allowed to sit by the edge. His tone and demeanor were condescending‚Äîhe made us feel like we didn‚Äôt matter and that he was doing us a favor by seating us at all.

The worst part? We could clearly see another couple seated in the sofa area, along with several other small groups of just 3‚Äì4 people. So the explanation we were given didn‚Äôt hold up, and it felt like we were being singled out unfairly.

We stayed briefly only because the entrance fee included two drinks, but left as soon as we could. The DJ didn‚Äôt help the mood either.

Overall, it was a very disappointing experience. There are plenty of other rooftop venues in KL that offer stunning views and treat guests with respect. I strongly recommend exploring those instead. Helipad is not worth your time or money.

First, the El Cero Eco Fresh Salad (RM27).
The menu lists Spanish chicken sausage slices, kidney beans, roasted peppers, chickpeas, croutons, spinach, rocket leaves, Parmesan, green apple, and olive oil.
What arrived: missing the sausage, beans, peppers, and chickpeas. After pointing it out, the staff remade it - this time only adding the sausage‚Ä¶Still no beans, no peppers, no chickpeas.
When I asked again, I was told they had ‚Äúadded more croutons.‚Äù
Really? A few croutons to replace all the missing vegetables?
That‚Äôs not a substitution, that‚Äôs cutting corners.

They offered another complimentary salad as apology, but honestly, the entire dining experience was already ruined.
A customer shouldn‚Äôt have to chase the kitchen twice just to get what the menu promises.

Second, the lamb dish.
Served last, it was so tough that cutting into it made the whole table wobble, and chewing it was close to impossible.
We simply gave up on the dish.

While the staff on the floor tried to stay polite, the inconsistency from the kitchen and the lack of genuine service recovery left us disappointed.

I honestly don‚Äôt understand what‚Äôs with the overrated reviews on Google. There are plenty of restaurants nearby.
Do walk around and you‚Äôll definitely find a better spot for a lovely evening.
Not a place I‚Äôd recommend.

I would like to give credits to a staff named Sanja who did his best to explain.

name: Lot 10 Hutong
address: lot 10, 50, Bukit Bintang Rd, Bukit Bintang, 55100 Kuala Lumpur, Federal Territory of Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia
text:
‚Äã"Hutong Food Court Review: A Disappointing Culinary Experience"
‚Äã"Our recent visit to Hutong Food Court, inspired by a positive YouTube review, unfortunately proved to be a significant letdown. It became apparent that the venue's primary target audience is tourists, as we noted that a majority of the stalls (approximately 90%) were operated by foreign workers. This observation prompted us to lower our expectations for an authentic local food experience.

‚ÄãTo provide a fair assessment, we ordered three different dishes from separate vendors. Our findings are as follows:
‚Äã1)Claypot Foochow Mee Sua (RM25+): This dish was the most disappointing of our selections. It lacked the characteristic and expected aroma of red wine, offering a one-dimensional and overwhelmingly salty flavor profile. The high sodium content made it difficult to consume more than a few bites.

‚Äã2)Wanton Mee Soup with Dumplings (RM17+): The dumplings were satisfactory; however, the wanton noodles had a powerful and unpleasant alkaline taste, which completely overpowered the broth and other components. This issue significantly impacted the overall enjoyment of the dish.

‚Äã3)Fried Oyster Omelette (RM19.90): This dish was a poor value for its price. The portion was remarkably small, containing only five tiny, pre-boiled oysters. The omelette itself was bland and lacked the rich, savory flavor one would expect from a proper fried oyster omelette.
‚ÄãIn summary, Hutong Food Court offers small portion sizes at a premium price. The quality of the dishes we sampled was subpar, lacking the authenticity and flavor that are hallmarks of true Malaysian street food.

text:
I visited this place after seeing countless positive influencer reviews, but honestly, it feels overrated and nowhere near the hype.

1. Nei Sooru with Mutton Thanni Kurma
The nei sooru had no ghee aroma or flavor ‚Äî it tasted like plain rice. The mutton kurma was thin, watery, and lacked any real taste. For over RM30, the portion was very disappointing: a small bowl with just three pieces of mutton, mostly bone, and the meat wasn‚Äôt tender. Hard to understand how this dish gained so much praise.

2. Karupatti Halwa
This was the biggest letdown. The texture was dense and hard, almost like dodol ‚Äî I could literally stand a spoon in it. Taste-wise, it was overwhelmingly sugary (felt like 95% sugar) with no balance of karupatti flavor. If you want proper karupatti halwa, I‚Äôd recommend trying Mulaga Restaurant instead.

3. Mutton Kola Urundai
Again, no real mutton flavor came through. The outside was hard, clearly over-fried, and unpleasant to bite into.

As for their coffee and tea, nothing worth commenting on.

Overall, the food didn‚Äôt live up to expectations, especially at these prices.

name: Restoran Win Heng Seng
address: 183, Jln Imbi, Imbi, 55100 Kuala Lumpur, Wilayah Persekutuan Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia
text:
Came here to check out the yong tau foo cheong fun. Indeed, the cheong fun was silky soft and came covered in KL style brown sauce. It was nostalgically sweet and savory. The YTF was a mixed bag however - the ladyfinger was nicely filled and was cooked just right, not too mushy. The fried tau kee and etc were oily and chewy - not pleasant to eat. The eggplant too was nicely stuffed but abit overcooked and was mushy.

We also shared a plate of the wanton mee, which turned out surprisingly well balance. The noodle wasn't the QQ type like in HK, but the overall balance of the sauce was noteworthy.
Indeed, an interesting kopitiam to take note.

name: Muhibbah Seafood Restaurant | Halal
address: Jalan Seri Penchala, Kampung Sungai Penchala, 60000 Kuala Lumpur, Wilayah Persekutuan Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia
text:
Honestly, I won't give it another try.

Service: horrendous. Arrogant people. From booking of event till day of event, nothing is right. Slow response to messages, missed a serving of food, staff lack of attention and slow service. One of the item (deep fried tofu) no stock since days ago but no one from the restaurant informed us, until on the event day itself. They replaced with tofu claypot but served on a flat plate.

Food:
- Sotong Sambal is spicy and tasty but a bit hard to chew tho.
- The deep fried fish in soy and garlic sauce is tasty, crispy on the outside and juicy on the inside.
- Buttered prawn's egg floss was crispy and well seasoned.

Let's not mention the other food we ordered (total 10 items).

The worse taste award goes to their Chinese fried rice. At RM22, it's definitely no value for money. It's totally bland. Even a pack of Adabi fried rice taste so much better. Doesn't look tempting at all. And this is the item which they overlooked from our paid menu. Can see it's a rush job to cook when everyone almost going home.

Environment: Honestly, with an open space like that, they need to be very alert that stray cats and dogs "frequently visits" the restaurant. It's extremely unhygienic as the cat was sitting comfortably at the chairs. They should at least wipe clean the dirt and bacteria.

Think about it. There are still many other Chinese muslim restaurants which serves better food and a more reasonable price, with better service.

name: Kin Kin Restaurant
address: 40, Jln Dewan Sultan Sulaiman 1, Chow Kit, 50300 Kuala Lumpur, Wilayah Persekutuan Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia
text:
We waited almost an hour for just two bowls of noodles, while other customers who came later had already finished their meals. Traditional way to take order. When we checked with the owner, the response was dismissive, saying that ‚Äúgood food takes time‚Äù and even suggesting we could eat at the restaurant across the street if we didn‚Äôt want to wait.

We also ordered the mixed meat ball, fish ball, and taukee. Unfortunately, two pieces of taukee had visible mold inside, which we only noticed after eating some. Although the restaurant replaced them, one of the replacement pieces still had mold. This is a serious food safety concern.

When our noodles finally arrived, the taste was average, similar to a typical pan mee. The chili was left uncovered, which raised hygiene concerns as well. The only item we found enjoyable was the fish ball.

Overall, the service, hygiene, and food quality were disappointing. Hopefully the they can take this feedback seriously and improve.

I chose this place to celebrate a special occasion and spent RM1k just to felt rushed and unappreciated.

5. We still had food on the table and hadn‚Äôt even cut the birthday cake.

6. Rushed to grill everything, finish our food, chug drinks, and blow the cake in a hurry.

7. Left by 8:00PM. Waited for our Grab till 8:15PM. During that time, we saw NO customers entering or waiting outside (it was a Monday night).

8. Understand the need for time limits during peak hours but when it‚Äôs not busy, some flexibility would really improve the customer experience.

name: Batang Kali Bamboo Briyani
address: Bamboo Briyani, 1, Jalan Kelah 1, taman sri kelah, 44300 Batang Kali, Selangor, Malaysia
text:
Came over after genting trip.
Overall in my humble opinion... this shop has been just too hyped up.
If you are planning to go... Please LOWER your expectations. Thank God I did not go there hungry.
They need to get staffs who speak basic English or malay or Tamil.. They can understand or speak neither. Every thing we asked they jus sed ok or nod with no reply. So I can't fully say poor service cause they are trying to understand you and serve.
They did come n ask if everything was fine and all order arrived.
The food was overall average.
The best tasting was the alapuzha squid briyani.. Which was at a whopping rm59.
That's just too much for a shop in nowhere batang Kali.
The other bamboo chicken n mutton briyani tasted very very ordinary. As mentioned by other reviewers it's nowhere close to the spices and taste you expect from briyani. There was practically no curd in the raita.. A dry onion side dish.
The so called premium coffee and chai was a rip off with dramatic presentation...
The chai tasted like benadryl mixed with tea n chocolate. Nauseously sweet.
The coffee was very sweet as well tasted like a 3 in 1 mixture.

What topped it was refusal to provide hot water. I understand you want to make money from your drinks thus you don't want to provide warm/plain water but I requested for hot water for my son as he was not well. I can buy mineral water from shop.. Where else can I get hot water? You can make hot green tea but can't provide hot water? Who are you trying to scam?

And yeah i will neva step into this shop ever again.
Total paid was 178 for 5 dishes n 3 drinks n 2 water bottles

I think you can walk in to any shops in sentul or Brickfields and get a much better experience of briyani whether being Bamboo or not. For a cheaper price.

The 2 stars was for the squid briyani..nothing else.

name: Papadums Curry House
address: 13, Jalan Sepadu C 25/C, Seksyen 25, 40400 Shah Alam, Selangor, Malaysia
text:
Absolutely disappointed with the way my recent food order was handled. The food was delivered in such an awful, messy, and unappetizing manner ‚Äî honestly, even my pet at home gets served better than this.

What‚Äôs even more shocking was the response when I called the restaurant directly. Instead of taking accountability or even attempting to resolve the issue, I was told, "We can't do anything because Grab has a monopoly in the market."

Seriously? That's possibly the lamest excuse I've heard from any F&B business. If you are unable to maintain a basic standard in how your food reaches customers, perhaps it's better to stop offering delivery altogether rather than pushing the blame and washing your hands off the responsibility.

Food delivery isn't just about taste ‚Äî it's also about presentation, care, and respect for customers paying for your service. Blaming the delivery platform doesn't take away from the fact that the food left your kitchen in that state.

Rest assured ‚Äî this is the first and last time I‚Äôll be ordering from here. There are plenty of other places that take pride in their food from kitchen to doorstep

*On your response to my review above*

"Wow, what a beautifully worded apology ‚Äî almost poetic! I‚Äôm genuinely impressed by how much care you‚Äôve put into saying you‚Äôll improve things. If only half that effort had gone into actually preparing or delivering the food, maybe we wouldn't be here. But hey, at least I now know that you ‚Äústrive‚Äù for better service‚Ä¶ emphasis on strive, clearly not achieve. As for giving you another chance ‚Äî I‚Äôll think about it next time I‚Äôm in the mood for disappointment served cold"

name: Tonkatsu by Ma Maison √¢‚Ç¨¬¢ 1 Utama
address: LG-226, 1 Utama Shopping Centre, Lebuh Bandar Utama, Bandar Utama, 47800 Petaling Jaya, Selangor, Malaysia
text:
During our visit, we discovered that the salt grinder placed on our table was rusted. We requested a replacement, only to be given another bottle that was also rusty. This is completely unacceptable. Rust in food service items is a serious health hazard ‚Äî it can contaminate food and potentially cause foodborne illnesses.

Frankly, for a restaurant that positions itself as a premium dining establishment, this is appalling. We expect high standards of hygiene, food safety, and customer experience ‚Äî none of which were met during our visit. It is extremely disappointing and frankly infuriating that such negligence has occurred not once, but twice, within the same visit.

This experience not only ruined our meal, but also left us with a strong sense of discomfort and distrust. It is hard to justify the high prices when such basic hygiene standards are clearly being overlooked.

I strongly urge you to investigate this matter immediately and ensure that corrective actions are taken. I expect a proper explanation and assurance that steps will be taken to prevent this from happening again ‚Äî not just to us, but to any other customer.

name: La Padella Western & Italian
address: Jalan 3, Kampung Pasir Puchong, 47100 Puchong, Selangor, Malaysia
text:
Tried La Padella in Puchong and had a pretty decent experience. Ordered the Grilled Chicken Breast and Grilled Chicken Chop, paired with a Teh O Ais. The portions were just right‚Äînot too much, not too little.

The chicken was cooked well, and while the black pepper sauce was flavorful, it slightly overpowered the dish. Still enjoyable though. The chicken chop came with a generous serving of fries‚Äîmaybe even a bit too much for my preference, but some would appreciate that.

The setup is casual‚Äînothing fancy but not shabby either. One suggestion would be to improve the ventilation, as it can get a bit stuffy when the place fills up. That said, it had a decent crowd, and prices are reasonable, especially if you're looking to satisfy a Western food craving without breaking the bank.

Overall, a solid spot for a casual meal.

name: Food Republic at Pavilion Bukit Jalil
address: Level 1, Pavilion, Persiaran Jalil Utama, Bukit Jalil, 57000 Kuala Lumpur, Federal Territory of Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia
text:
Tried Food Republic @ Pavilion Bukit Jalil for a change, but left underwhelmed.

Instead of dining in a regular restaurant, we decided to try out the food court for some variety. Unfortunately, the experience didn‚Äôt quite meet expectations.

1st stop: Thai Cuisine stall
Ordered the Pattaya Fried Rice ‚Äî it was underwhelming. The rice wasn‚Äôt fully wrapped in the egg, and the overall taste was quite plain and lacking depth. It felt more like a rushed attempt than an actual dish.

2nd stop: Yong Tau Foo
Picked peria, terong, fuyong gulung, pok segi tiga, and siew pak choy. Sadly, the peria and terong were undercooked, and the curry was oily with a very subdued flavor. It didn‚Äôt feel hearty or satisfying.

3rd stop: Melayu & Padang stall
We had nasi putih, ayam madu, and telur dadar. While the taste was okay, the portion was small and the price didn‚Äôt justify it. Definitely felt overpriced for what we got.

I appreciate the idea of offering various stalls to cater to different cravings, but in this case, the quality of food and the pricing just didn‚Äôt match up. Hope to see improvements in taste, portioning, and overall value.

name: Coco Island Street Food
address: 104, Persiaran Gurney, 10250 George Town, Pulau Pinang, Malaysia
text:
Coco Island Food Court is one of those places that draws both locals and tourists, thanks to its convenient location near popular attractions. The atmosphere feels lively and open, with a mix of stalls offering local and international cuisines. However, while the selection looks appealing at first glance, the overall quality varies quite a bit from stall to stall.

One of the highlights for me was the fresh coconut water. It‚Äôs incredibly refreshing, especially on a hot day, and has that distinct pandan-like aroma that gives it a naturally sweet and fragrant twist ‚Äî something quite special compared to the usual coconuts you find elsewhere. On the other hand, the stall serving Chinese food was quite disappointing. The dishes lacked seasoning and depth of flavor, coming across as bland and uninspired. It felt like a missed opportunity, considering how flavorful Chinese cuisine can be when done right.

The fish and chips, however, were surprisingly decent. The fish was crispy on the outside, flaky on the inside, and paired well with the tartar sauce. It‚Äôs a safe option if you‚Äôre unsure of what to try. That said, prices here are definitely on the higher side ‚Äî likely due to the tourist traffic in the area. You‚Äôre paying as much for the convenience and atmosphere as for the food itself. Overall, Coco Island Food Court offers a pleasant spot to relax and enjoy a drink, but food quality can be hit or miss depending on your choice.

name: Laksalicious
address: 117-117A, Jalan Hutton, George Town, 10050 George Town, Pulau Pinang, Malaysia
text:
As assam laksa lovers, we‚Äôve tried many versions across Penang, and Laksalicious caught our attention through Google, especially with its Michelin recognition. Naturally, we decided to give it a try.

Unfortunately, it didn‚Äôt quite suit our taste. The thick noodles used were not what we expected, not really chewy like we had or supposed to be.The soup or broth itself felt rather diluted compared to the rich, tangy flavour we usually enjoy in assam laksa. It doesn‚Äôt have the sourness kick. On a brighter note, their signature Laksa Mojito was quite unique and refreshing, though the paper straw provided turned soggy halfway, making it difficult to finish the drink comfortably.

We also tried the Nyonya Sago Gula Malacca, but it was rather underwhelming. The sago itself was bland, and since the gula malacca could not be absorbed or properly dipped through the sago, the overall flavour was lacking. A touch of sweetness in the sago itself might have balanced it better.

Service-wise, our experience could have been better. We arrived around 11.20am, but no staff came forward to offer us a seat or provide chairs while waiting. Standing outside under the hot afternoon sun was not the most pleasant start to our meal.

name: Anamika Spice Kitchen
address: 412-1-3, Jalan Bukit Dumbar, Bukit Dumbar, 11600 Jelutong, Pulau Pinang, Malaysia
text:
Thank you for the detailed response. I‚Äôd like to clarify a few points for Anamika:

Firstly, the agreed time of 3:00 PM‚Äîwell past regular lunch hours‚Äîwas not imposed by us but offered by your team, with a choice between 11:00 AM or 3:00 PM. Due to our travel schedule, we opted for the 3:00 PM slot. So, the concern about interrupting your lunch crowd does not quite apply here.

This is not about who recommended your restaurant or the timing. I am simply stating facts and presenting a photo of the food served at RM35 per person. I‚Äôm leaving it to the public to decide if the value matches what was delivered. I do not expect a further response from Anamika, as I believe the discussion is now conflicted.

To be fair, I acknowledge that the coffee, payasam, and mango pachadi were well received. However, the main dishes fell short of expectations, especially for the price point. Also, we did not request to be served; we could have easily helped ourselves since we paid for the full amount. The way it played out made it seem as though we were receiving food as a favour, when in fact it was fully paid for.

Additionally, there was a significant amount of food left over, which to me indicates dissatisfaction with quality‚Äînot quantity. I also paid separately for the two vegetarian meals, so I don‚Äôt believe it's appropriate for you to bring that up in your explanation.

The fact that something as basic as papadams had to be specially requested, despite the RM35 per head cost, also says a lot. I won‚Äôt be engaging further in a back-and-forth. I‚Äôll let the public judge based on the facts and the pictures of what was served.

Additionally, I‚Äôve shared my feedback with the relevant consumer authorities in Malaysia, who are currently monitoring pricing practices in the F&B sector. Let them assess whether this is acceptable and fair to the wider public.

Just for the record: the mutton had a strong odour, and the chicken‚Äîdescribed as sambal‚Äîresembled and tasted more like kurma. These are honest reflections of what was experienced.

No more response is required from yourself.

text:
I recently visited Aro Restaurant around 3 PM for a late lunch. Upon arrival, we were warmly welcomed by an uncle who provided great service, explaining the menu thoroughly and taking our orders efficiently. We ordered two meals along with a side of Gobi Manchurian (vegan).

The food itself was fine, but we couldn‚Äôt finish everything. When I asked a lady (who I believe might be the manager or director) to pack the leftover Gobi Manchurian for takeaway, her response was both surprising and disappointing. She mentioned that they don‚Äôt bring food back to the kitchen to pack leftovers and handed me a small burger box and a plastic bag, expecting us to pack the food ourselves.

I found this approach unprofessional and felt it lacked basic customer service. As a paying customer, I believe it‚Äôs reasonable to expect assistance with packing leftovers, especially in a dine-in setting. Her tone and attitude didn‚Äôt help the situation either, leaving a sour impression.

While the initial service was pleasant, this incident overshadowed our experience. It‚Äôs a shame, as small gestures of hospitality can make a big difference in maintaining a restaurant‚Äôs reputation. I hope the management takes this feedback constructively to improve their service standards.

I had the same food with my wife for lunch and breakfast she did not had diarrhea so probably the cause is from the dinner i dine in.

In conclusion the ambience 0/10, food 3/10 service 10/10.

If you are very rich and want to have an bad dining experience i would recommend to go otherwise go to other places

name: Sushi King Ipoh Parade
address: Lot G22, Ground Floor, Ipoh Parade, 105, Jalan Sultan Abdul Jalil, 30450 Ipoh, Perak, Malaysia
text:
I haven‚Äôt visited Sushi King for many years until today. Unfortunately, the experience was disappointing, and I feel compelled to share my feedback‚Äînot to criticise for the sake of it, but with the hope that improvements can be made, especially for such a well-known and established brand in Malaysia.

I completely understand the F&B industry is going through a tough time, and manpower shortage is a real challenge. My comments here are made with that in mind, and out of genuine concern for the customer experience.

Here‚Äôs what happened during my visit:
1.	Lack of staff presence ‚Äì When I arrived, there was no one at the cashier or in the dining area to greet or seat us. We had to wait without knowing what to do next.
2.	Slow and uncoordinated food service ‚Äì One of the food orders arrived and was almost finished before the rest of the items (two other dishes and drinks) were even served. The system showed the items as ‚Äúprepared,‚Äù but clearly, they were not brought out in time, likely due to lack of manpower.
3.	Quality of food ‚Äì The salmon bento was disappointing: the salmon didn‚Äôt seem fresh, the flavour was bland, and the rice was cold.
4.	Udon had a similar issue‚Äîit felt like it was left sitting for too long before reaching our table, as the temperature and texture were off.

5. The tablet being used to order food is oily.

6.	Payment process ‚Äì Again, we had to wait at the counter because no one was there to attend to us, adding to the frustration.

I say all this not to be harsh, but because I believe Sushi King is capable of much better. It‚Äôs a recognised brand with a good reputation, and I hope the management at Ipoh Parade can take this feedback seriously and make the necessary adjustments.

Customers want to support local outlets, especially during hard times, but basic service quality and food freshness must still be maintained.

name: Super HLT Restaurant (Ipoh) Sdn Bhd
address: 274, Jalan Sultan Iskandar, 30000 Ipoh, Perak, Malaysia
text: We were here for my dad‚Äôs and Uncle‚Äôs birthday.  Celebration. My uncle came 2 weeks ago to order some special dishes and there were 17 of us. We were given 2 tables of 9 and 8 person respectively. since the big table could only manage of group of 13. When we arrived at the restaurant, some car parks were reserved for us so that was handy since we had old people with us.  When we got into the restaurant, my Uncle was disappointed that we weren‚Äôt given a room for our private function. We were seated at the big hall. It took another 25 mins before the first dish arrived. It was the sea cucumber with abalone and other stuffs like water chestnut. The sea cucumber while seems a bit tougher than usual but still ok. The taste was good as there were abalone that came with it.  After the first meal, it took another 15 mins before the suckling pig was served. The dish was garnished with some steam buns and spring onions. To my disappointment, the suckling pig has a very strong gamy taste. The steam buns were not as soft as I wished it to. It was kind of felt like the bun had a dense texture. The third dish was the baked crab with salt and pepper. The first bite I had when I tasted it was salt. It was just too much! Luckily the crab meat was fresh and soft to save the dish. Then came the 2.5kg of Sultan fish. My table has only 8 people and imagine we had to eat the whole fish. It was way too big for the 8 of us and the soya sauce again was too salty to my liking. Kind of spoil the taste of the fish. I bet the chef never considered the number of dishes we had ordered and also the number of people seated on the table.  Kind of felt like a ripped off. We ended up packing 1/3 of the fish home. What a shame! By the time we finished the fish, we already so full and no appetite to eat the rest. The big head prawn in supreme sauce came after that. This was really sinful with the black caramelized supreme sauce. I found it too sweet and the prawn were overcooked and the fresh was very tough. What a way to spoil the big prawn! The stirred fried lotus stem with bangkuang, snow peas and cashew nuts was served soon after. The dish was kind of blend and I hardly taste any taste except the bangkuang which was a bit sour which was unusual. This was definitely not one memorable dish for the night. The last dish was the char siew noodles which represented the longevity noodles served for any birthday celebration. It turned out to be another disappointment where the noodles were very overcooked and lost it bounciness. I would gave this a pass too! Then the desserts were served, first was the longevity buns with lotus seed paste. Second came the mochi with peanuts and lastly the dragon fruits with sago sweet soup. We were just overwhelmed with the amount of food and feeling too full. The chef should have advised the host on the amount of food ordered if it was too much. They could have suggested the 2 tables shared one 2.5 kg of fish instead of having 2 x 2.5kg fish per table.  Instead of feeling happy and satisfied, we were disappointed with the food quality and the amount of food served was just insane. The bill came out to a whopping rm3100‚Äôper table which was shocking. I don‚Äôt think I would ever come back again for the poor quality and service given.

Poor cleanliness. Walls and floor are all sticky. Need to do a proper clean up. Stickers all over the place. Can drinks are all over the place, messy area. Ambience surely not good. If it rains then you get a cool breeze coming in kalau tidak bau asap dari gas masak. Ventilation need to improve.

Reasonable price got to say it's cheap.

Double roti telur, roti telur, Bru coffee, teh Ais, masala tea - total RM14.70

I am a fan of indian food and restaurants. There are many Indian restaurants opening and rising up, note the competition is real. I hope that there will be changed and that you will see what needs change.

Anyway, I wish that rajamah will further improve and get better. I wish you the best in the coming future.

name: Souper Tang @ City Square
address: J4-21, City Square, 106-108, Jalan Wong Ah Fook, Bandar Johor Bahru, 80000 Johor Bahru, Johor Darul Ta'zim, Malaysia
text:
Disclaimer: sorry I did eat some food and then took the photo, my bad.

Total price : 240 ringgit ( including the lemonade with enzyme)

I didnt fabricated anything, it is exactly as how it went.

Went on Saturday 19th April 2025, around 12.30pm. Clearly almost everywhere is crowded because it's lunch hour.

Went in as there was no queue, but the restaurant was fairly crowded, and stepped outside to wait for someone to perhaps notice us and let us in since I didn't wanted to just barge in.

But I saw a worker but definitely an auntie from my perspective using phone and wasn't sure watching something or what, but heads down and engrossed on it while manning the entrance. ü§î so I just approached and asked if there was table for two, which a lady guided us.

So we sat down and choose the menu and went onto order. Clearly understaffed. There are around 20 tables with 2-3 staff serving and taking orders.

So we had to caught the attention of the young female staff to take our order and she wrote it down and went to take another person's order and we waited afterwards.

Past 20 minutes no one came down to check on us or serve our food. So given that I've been in FnB, I gave the benefit of doubt, and just checked in with the same lady to perhaps pass us the order invoice and she told her she will get it but another 10 minute she breeze past us and didn't give us anything.

I don't mean to say anything bad, but it got me wandered, what could be the problem.

So we got the guy staff instead to check, and he got back to us stating that we didn't order anything and asked who took our order and when we shared, he just shook his head, so I guess he knew it as well.

Then we got our food.

As you can see in the photo, I got to say, the soup good. Everything else, pretty much suck. I gotta be honest. This place has some great soup and really I feel it's worth it. But everything else it's very questionable.

Also, it's seems specialised in soup, yet only when we are ready to order, the staff tell us 80% of the soup wasn't available? And it was only 12.30pm so if most of it is not available, what are they selling exactly???

Usually in msia, I don't get such unpleasant experience in terms of food, but this place wasn't beyond acceptable.

You can be the judge, and if you want soup, I'd recommend, but everything else, haha...it's entirely up to you.

I think they do excel at photo editing skill üòÄ

name: Sushi King City Square
address: Lot MB, 01, Basement Level 1, 106 & 108, Jalan Wong Ah Fook, Bandar Johor Bahru, 80000 Johor Bahru, Johor Darul Ta'zim, Malaysia
text:
I was really disappointed with my recent visit to Sushi King. We waited over 20 minutes for our sushi, which is unusually long considering we didn‚Äôt order any cooked items. Sushi shouldn‚Äôt take this long to prepare.

When the food finally arrived, it looked unappetising (see attached pictures). The salmon looked like cat food and was drowned in an excessive amount of seaweed. The salmon slices were thin, uneven, and just poorly presented overall.

Service was equally underwhelming ‚Äî no apology or acknowledgment of the delay. It felt like the staff didn‚Äôt care. There was not even a thank you when I paid the bill.

Definitely expected better quality and efficiency from a place like this.

My recommendation, Is to walk five minutes from here to komtar and have a way better quality meal and fresh products at Sushi Zenmai! I regret trying this place. And I will never recommend this to anyone.

name: Nimmies Pastry Cafe
address: 171, Jln Beringin, Taman Melodies, 80250 Johor Bahru, Johor Darul Ta'zim, Malaysia
text:
Don‚Äôt come for main course.. (review for main course, not their bakeries)

Have been wanting to try this place a for a long time. Before entering the cafe, already accepted the fact it‚Äôs going to be an expensive place given the location and the atmosphere but the foods are just disappointing.

The Cajun Chicken Aglio Olio, totally disappointed the moment the dish is served. Looks like they just throw the chicken on the top, nothing like shown. For the taste, hmm it tastes below average, already asked for less salt but the pasta still tasted v salty. The chicken looks & taste like the average  chicken.

RM38 Nasi lemak - served with overcooked chicken, so dry that we didn‚Äôt even finish. My brother commented it seems like an overnight chicken which has been re-fried multiple times. Tho the rice has a v nice fragrance. This price point I would rather go to orixxtxl kxxi or the txxst for nasi lemak.

I love hojicha, but I felt like the sweetness has overpowered the significance taste of hojicha. (This could be personal preference)

Last words, main courses are really disappointing however it seems like this place is famous for bakery which we didn‚Äôt order any. If you want to come maybe go for their bakeries first.

Staff are friendly, places are insta-worthy.

I have been a regular patron of this restaurant for years. It‚Äôs a well-known Indian eatery in the area, and although it may not serve what I would call authentic Indian food, I notice that many Indian locals frequent the place.

The restaurant is best known for a few dishes, including their Indian set lunch, where customers choose dishes from a display counter, and roti starting at 3:30 p.m., along with tandoori chicken and naan. As for drinks, their previous signature beverages included "blu" (a mix of coffee and milk tea), coffee, and milk tea. However, it‚Äôs important to note that some of the drinks are not freshly made-to-order. Instead, they seem to pre-boil the tea and store it in containers before mixing with milk and serving it.

During my latest visit, after finishing my meal, I was sipping on a milk tea (teh tarik) when I noticed something unusual in the drink. At first, I thought it was a tea leaf, but after spitting it out, I discovered it was a fly. I immediately reported this to a waiter, but unfortunately, I received no response. When I later informed the supervisor (also acting as cashier) while paying the bill, I was told the fly may have gotten in when the drink was prepared. While I didn‚Äôt ask for a replacement or refund, for obvious reasons, I would have appreciated a better response or at least an apology.

Given the lack of concern for hygiene, I don‚Äôt plan to return unless there‚Äôs a clear improvement in their standards.

address: Kampung Nyior Chabang, 07000 Langkawi, Kedah, Malaysia
text:
Feedback on My Experience at KAKA Caf√© ‚Äì 7th October 2025
I‚Äôve been a regular customer at KAKA for many years, which shows how much I‚Äôve appreciated their food, presentation, reasonable prices, and value for portion sizes.

However, I had a very disappointing experience last night, 7th October 2025.

As a regular, I know the caf√© usually doesn‚Äôt accept phone orders. But due to our long-standing trust, they accepted my second phone order after many years of dining there.

At 8:50 PM, I called to place an order for 4 dishes while I was still at the office (approximately a 7-minute drive, 4.1km away). At 9:08 PM, while I was just 1km away and heading there,

I received a call from the owner. In an arrogant tone, she said in Bahasa:

‚ÄúSatgi kalau makanan sejuk, jangan dok salahkan kami na.‚Äù
(Translation: ‚ÄúIf the food is cold later on, don‚Äôt blame us, ok!‚Äù)

Honestly, I was shocked. Where is the courtesy? That completely ruined my dinner mood.

When I arrived one minute later, I saw a staff member placing the 4 dishes on a table‚Äîperfectly timed at just 18 minutes after the order was placed (which is unusually fast, considering it normally takes 40 minutes to an hour, depending on how busy it is).

The owner approached me and apologized. I told her:
‚ÄúYou shouldn‚Äôt speak to a customer like that. I‚Äôve been supporting your caf√© for many years. If I couldn‚Äôt make it on time or had to cancel, you could‚Äôve simply called me and even charged me. You know where my office is.‚Äù

Sadly, last night was my final dinner at KAKA.
GOODBYE FOREVER.

name: POUND
address: L1-29, Jesselton Mall, 3, Jln Haji Saman, 88000 Kota Kinabalu, Sabah, Malaysia
text:
Expensive for no reason, with super small portions for bland tasting food. Goodluck trying to get the waiter‚Äôs attention.

Came here for anniversary dinner and thought to treat ourselves to the house special: sticky BBQ ribs. We also tried the truffles and caesar salad.

The ribs were the driest we ever had, with no gravy or sauce and was super bland. Wondering which part of it was sticky and it costs almost RM100.

The truffle fries had some burnt pieces of fries and the portion was smalller than the already small plate. The caesar salad was devoid of any complexity of flavours and were also super dry, served with a cold hard boiled eggs.

All the dishes that came out looked nothing like in the menu. Despite charging an exorbitant amount the dishes looked cheap, poorly garnished and presented. Not to mention the dirty cutleries being presented us, who knows if it was washed properly or is being reused.

This place used to be something, with a nice ambience and lighting. Now you eat under bright lights and wave your hand frantically to get the waiters attention. Nobody in the restaurant looked like theyre having a good time and bare in mind it‚Äôs a weekday night and not peak hour weekend.

Falling victim to their own greed of overcharging customers for a subpar experience, a total waste of RM200. If you want to celebrate something special, this is not the place. A disappointing experience.

name: City Food Corner (CFC Kota Kinabalu City Centre)
address: Ground Floor, Block J, Lot 10, Jln Dua Puluh, Sinsuran Complex, 88000 Kota Kinabalu, Sabah, Malaysia
text:
First time visiting, one of the long standing 24hr local restaurants located in the heart of Kota Kinabalu.

The menu is quite vast offering multiple cuisines from fried rice to nasi lemak to local Mee tuaran(Chinese egg noodle).

Drinks are pretty standard but super low quality, beware of the sweetness and condensed milk.

They also have many confectionaries from bread to muffins, swiss rolls.

The service is as you would expect with counter pay & table service.

The atmosphere gives an authentic feel of local Sabah but we were constantly haggled by outsiders to purchase bread for them. Even after giving them some spare change(RM10 in total, yes multiple members from the same group kept coming), they will not stop haggling and eyeing us during our visit at the shop. We were frankly really appalled, just something to take note of while you are there.

The food that stood out positively to me was the basic minced meat Mee tuaran, pls do not order the seafood Mee tuaran as it was much less flavourful and plain compared to the basic ver for a much higher price..

Overall, I would avoid this place if possible, but a relatively 'autentic' experience nonetheless...

name: Kalamata's Cafe KK (Warisan Square)
address: AG03, Warisan Square, Jln Tun Fuad Stephens, 88000 Kota Kinabalu, Sabah, Malaysia
text:
Did not meet expectations considering the 4.5 rating (at time of writing). Quite dissatisfied.

Had the Lamb Varuval and fish and chips.
The guy attending told us the chef was new and it was his first day, maybe that was the issue.

Lamb Varuval meat was soft and fresh as promised and the flavour was quite reasonable but that's where it ends. Apparently this dish is supposed to be oily (the staff told us in retrospect). It was extremely oily, both the lamb dish and the rice. The excessive oil detracting from the other nice flavours. Some will love it,...

The lamb dish was approx 70% bone and lamb fat. Again there are those that will be stimulated by the thought of all that lamb fat...
See before and after photos. The one that looks messier is what's left after you pick out all the available protein. At RM 38+ it was very disappointing.

Fish and chips were cheaper but not a deal, The fish was reasonable but not special. Chips were mass market factory offerings.

Surprised by all of this considering the rave reviews others have left.

name: KKIA SEAFOOD √•¬©‚Ä†√ß¬Ω‚Äî√¶¬π¬æ√¶¬µ¬∑√©¬≤≈ì√©¬¶‚Ä† / KKIA SUP IKAN TUARAN
address: Kg Gayang Tuaran, 88902 Kota Kinabalu, Sabah, Malaysia
text:
Food Review:
Fish Tom Yum: The soup was overly sweet ‚Äî it tasted like a whole kilogram of sugar had been poured into it, which completely overpowered the traditional tom yum flavor.
Fish : I requested sweet and sour, but what I received was closer to a Kam Heong-style dish. It did not match the order at all.
Vegetables: The vegetables were far too salty and drenched in oil, making them unpleasant to eat.
Chicken: I ordered a chicken dish, but it never arrived. Despite there being hardly any customers, the restaurant still managed to miss the order.

Service:
The waiter seemed unmotivated and uninterested in their work. Service was very slow overall, even though the restaurant was not busy.

Atmosphere:
The surroundings of the restaurant are clean, and it benefits from a nice view of Mount Kinabalu. However, the tables were dirty and oily, which detracted from the overall dining experience.

Overall:
This restaurant did not live up to the expectations set by TikToker Lala Kerry's review. The food, service, and cleanliness all fell short. It seems the place is only popular because of its view, not the quality of its offerings.

name: The Lord's Cafe Tanah Rata
address: Jalan Besar, Tanah Rata, 39000 Tanah Rata, Pahang, Malaysia
text:
Nice little rustic place, makes one feel as though you've stepped back in time. Not hard to find, signs pasted all over the place with a huge noticeboard. Plus there's Google map.

Apple pie, normal. The dough/crust, seems a little under cooked/baked...
One of a kind Strawberry Scone was alright, it came to us warm enough, but otherwise just average. Maybe my taste buds are gone, or everyone else have never had scones before (definitely not 'best ever'), I don't know. Give it a try. Cream is from a standard cannister, a little too sweet. Thankfully it's balanced out with salted butter (extra RM 1 for a teaspoon size).

Didn't realise it's self-service, so we didn't know we've to pick up our own order. One of the staffs brought it over and did NOT do it gracefully. We wondered why we were given such a lousy attitude (until I read some of the comments here).

So - yeah. Thanks but no thanks. We shall explore other places.

name: Glory 78 Steamboat Snack Corner(bamboo biryani)
address: 59, Tanah Rata, 39000 Tanah Rata, Pahang, Malaysia
text:
The service and atmosphere were excellent, and I really enjoyed the beverages ‚Äî the Strawberry Ice Blended was refreshing and definitely worth the price.

However, when it came to the main highlight, the Signature Bamboo Briyani, it fell a little short of my expectations. While the dish was full of aromatic spices, it was under-seasoned and could use a touch more salt for balance. It would also be more pleasant if whole spices like cloves, cardamom, cinnamon, and bay leaves were enclosed in a spice sachet, so they don‚Äôt end up mixed throughout the rice. Accidentally biting into them in every spoonful can be quite off-putting.

The mutton chunks, although flavorful, were not as tender as expected. A bit more time in a pressure cooker would make them melt-in-the-mouth and elevate the overall experience.

The sides also felt a little underwhelming for the price. Considering the restaurant is in the heart of an agro-produce area, the coleslaw, cucumber, and tomato portions could be more generous ‚Äî a full scoop of coleslaw would make a big difference. The chutney was delicious, but the serving size (barely half a teaspoon) left me wishing for more. If portions are going to be that small, it might be better to omit them altogether.

name: Xin Yong Kee Restaurant at Genting Permai
address: P1, Jalan Permai, Genting Permai Avenue, 69000 Genting Highlands, Pahang, Malaysia
text:
SCAMMER alert!
Now I've just checked - they r Known for scamming, pls check other reviews here - ppl have written about it....

This tilapia is NOT 1KG but u still charge 1kg despite confrontations...

I'm not some1 who leave a bad review for people much (you can check the profile) but I need to write this down so ppl will be wary of these low life scammers...

I was having the fish alone so I asked the person who took my order how heavy the tilapia was and she said its about 900g-1kg... A bit heavy for a single person but I thought  didn't really matter as the price was fair @ 40rm a kg... So I thought ok.

1st red flag - upon confirming the order I was looking at the aquarium and saw the live tilapias but thought they were small ones  looking like 800+-g so I went to ask the waitress and told her I saw small fishes and I want the small ones instead.. She said minimum 900-1kg anyway...
Giving them the benefit of doubt, I was thinking The small ones didn't look that heavy but I thought ok nvm let's see what they will be giving, maybe my eye sight is bad and inside aquarium look different...

So when they served the tilapia, I had a good look at it and quite sure it was around 800g MAX MAX 900g so I asked the lady that took my order how heavy it was and she said its 1kg sharp... I told her this cannot be 1kg and of course she said it was and took to spoon to scoop up the tail to show me that it was - I'm not sure why she did that because there wasn't much on the tail anyway. But I thought ok nvm just accept it ....... Its my word against theirs..

As I was eating the fish and scooping up the flesh and head, I became more and more sure this was not 1kg due to the 1) size of the head, 2) size of bone and structure and 3) collar bone and belly... 2nd red flag.

3rd red flag - So after finishing the fish, I went to pay the bill at the counter and at the same time I asked how heavy was the fish they will be billing me... I saw the bill and the lady said 1kg... I told her it's not possible that's 1kg. And she became defensive without even checking with the kitchen or check out the whole issue... She just snapped at me and said some nonsense which I still don't get it which was something like they deboned the fish..... And in my head, I still remember going thru the bones so wdf does she mean by they ÂéªÈ™®... I'm just thinking like you don't even bother to double triple  check and understand the whole situation and double triple confirm if there was no human error and u just responded to me in a defensive manner, it must be you have already been scamming like this for a long time..

Anyway, I decided to just pay and write this down... Because obviously they will argue that it's 1kg anyhow...

Frankly speaking, the fish was around 800g (a size of tilapia I am very very familiar with as this was my usual portion when I eat) and max max 900g, I still can accept and wouldn't have written this down...
But because u insist it was 1kg and was defensive without even checking properly, I know your place is a total scam.....

My bill and photo of fish for every1 to judge.... Look at the size of the head - it's as small as the serving spoon (Âã∫Â≠êÔºâ.... Its not a lot of money, maybe a difference of 100-200g price (rm4-rm8), but in exchange for that, here is my honest review you earned for your scamming business...

BTW, I have whole tilapia THREE-FOUR times a week so I know roughly what the size is usually.. U cant fool every1...

Anyway, taste is bad too... Assam steam tasted just like cheap flavourings to make the sauce  and vege lack taste/flavour.. Soup was alright but nothing to shout about... Bring your money elsewhere like Gohtong Jaya...

name: Nasi Kandar Yasmeen Kulim
address: 38, Jalan Kota Kenari, Kota Kenari, 09000 Kulim, Kedah, Malaysia
text:
Thousands of reviews with a 4.3 avg score of a commercialized nasi kandar. If this is one of the best Kulim had to offer, then this town probably hasn't much good eatery places. I don't usually rate nasi kandar of this nature, only in the rare circumstances of slim pickings or glowing  recommendations and this one justified my opinion, however unqualified that may be, that commercialized nasi kandar are usually mediocre at best. This one is just bad.

The ayam madu is sweet like they pour the entire pack of sugar in the pot. There is no flavour beyond sugary sweet, just a mild chilli heat without much spices and mildly seasoned. I'd say this sauce is even suitable for chee cheong fun. The chicken was also over fried and thus is very tough for something you'd cook in a watery sauce. The only thing good is their rice which is firm, oily and has proper spices. If only they'd put in as much effort in their chicken dish. The price should be within the town's standard but slightly higher than the more established neighboring Bukit Metajam.

Taste factor: 2/10
Cuisine: nasi kandar

text:
Locals' food court. Heard the old sifus are all here. Food - many varieties, was told by locals the following are recommended:

Oyster omelette - good service and good taste. They sprinkled char choy on top making it unique.

ABC - standard but affordable at RM4 a bowl

First and last time here.

text:
Not worth a try, there are definitely better chai poh fish restaurants in Alor Setar. The fish was tasteless and not fresh at all, it seemed like sweet chai po was just used to cover up the blunt flavor. There were also many flies around, and customers were still being seated outdoors even though the area smelled rancid and unpleasant. I dined alone, which might be why I was placed outdoors, but it really affected the experience. When I gave feedback to the staff, they did not seem to take it seriously.

Reply:
Thanks for your reply, but I think it‚Äôs unnecessary to argue with customers who share honest feedback. I didn‚Äôt ask for compensation or replacement, I just wanted to highlight the hygiene and freshness issue so it can be improved. It‚Äôs understandable that solo diners get smaller tables, but placing customers outdoors where it smells rancid and has flies really affects the dining experience.

Also, how am I supposed to order more dishes when I‚Äôm dining alone? Feedback shouldn‚Äôt be dismissed just because I came by myself or didn‚Äôt order a lot. A good restaurant listens and improves, not blames the customer. Hope you understand and don‚Äôt take it the wrong way, thanks!

address: Lot 3794, 3795, Jalan Tuanku Munawir, Taman Bukit Lemon, 70000 Seremban, Negeri Sembilan, Malaysia
text:
I was extremely disappointed with my recent dining experience. First, the steamed fish was shockingly thin, almost translucent. It felt like they were being incredibly stingy with the portion. It was a real struggle to get any substantial meat from it, which was surprising, as I‚Äôve never encountered such a portion, even for just a few diners.

The oyster omelette was another letdown. The dish was overwhelmingly egg, with barely any oysters in sight. When I order an oyster omelette, I expect the oysters to be the highlight, not to have them hidden in an overcooked egg. It was clear they cut corners on the key ingredient.

The sweet and sour pork with the yam basket was likely the best dish of the meal, but even that had its flaws. The pork was decent, but the yam basket was a real disappointment. It lacked any crispness; instead, it was soggy and overly chewy, with a tough fried skin that was hard to enjoy. A yam basket should have a satisfying crunch, but this was completely missing.

The fried rice, however, was passable and didn't disappoint as much as the other dishes.

Overall, the meal fell far short of expectations, and considering the price, it‚Äôs certainly not worth it. I won‚Äôt be returning, though perhaps I‚Äôd consider trying other dishes if I did. Price is reasonable.

On a positive note, the place was clean and comfortable, providing a pleasant dining environment. However, the quality of the food unfortunately didn‚Äôt match the setting.

Dishes came quite some time‚Ä¶

name: Restoran DPantai & DPedas
address: Lot 2031, 1, Jalan Pantai Batu 10, Kampung Pantai, 71770 Seremban, Negeri Sembilan, Malaysia
text:
During our meal, we experienced some issues with the satay. The satay kambing appeared to be undercooked, and the satay tongkeng had a very sour taste, which might indicate the marinade had spoiled. When we brought this to the attention of the kitchen staff, they did not offer a verbal response but tasted the remaining undercooked satay kambing with very little onion and nasi impit for 9 sticks.

We did enjoy the other dishes: the kambing bakar, masak lemak daging salai, and homemade mushroom soup were delicious. The satay daging was also acceptable.

However, the service from the crew was disappointing. They did not smile and seemed indifferent to our presence.

Upon raising the issue a second time at the cashier, the cashier apologized and waived the charges for the satay kambing and satay tongkeng.

I hope the restaurant can improve the food quality, specifically for the satay, and also enhance their customer service, as I have been a loyal customer of their kambing perap for many years.

name: Tanah Aina Fareena Cafe ( SENI RIMBA RESTAURANT)
address: Lot 6073, 54.3km, Lebuhraya Karak, Kampung Lentang, 28600 Bentong, Pahang, Malaysia
text:
Went here on the insistence of the missus. Drove and drove and drove... and missed the turning cos the signboards are soooooo bad! Had to make a massive u-turn and finally got to the parking. Had to walk quite a bit on this makeshift bridge which they call "A bridge under a bridge".

Got there, sat down, and was attended to by a very polite gentleman. There's a lot of seating so take your pick. Just remember that if you sit near the river, you'll probably have to deal with screaming idiotic children playing. If you hate kids like I do, that's going to be a problem.

I got the nasi goreng Aina and the missus got the laksa Johor; we shared a cucur udang. Food finally came and it was definitely pretty... and that was it.

The fried rice was soooooo boring, and the missus said she's had better laksa at roadside stalls. The cucur udang was 1 prawn wrapped in a tonne of batter. Absolutely crap! Seems like this place gives more importance to figure than form; as long as it's pretty, it doesn't matter if it tastes atrocious.

My advice = if you're going to drive allllll the way from Klang Valley to go there for the food, please don't! You can find better food in a million different places. But if you want to drive to feed your camera, then yeah, it's worth it. Me, I'm NEVER going back again!

name: Amos Curry House
address: 17a, Jalan SG 3/16, Taman Sri Gombak, 68100 Batu Caves, Selangor, Malaysia
text:
I‚Äôve been to Amos Curry House several times this year, hoping each visit might redeem the last. The food? Genuinely good. But good food alone doesn‚Äôt make up for service that feels like an afterthought.

The staff consistently seem uninterested in the fact that customers exist. Even during non-peak hours, the pace is glacial and lack attentiveness

A few highlights from our recurring disappointment:

We‚Äôve sat for nearly 10 minutes without anyone acknowledging us. Eventually, we gave up and placed our own orders at the counter. Takeaway orders? Also ignored. We waited, only to discover our food had been packed and abandoned at the counter. If this is meant to be self-service, a sign would be a revolutionary idea.

Ordered tandoori chicken, specifically thigh meat. It arrived late, after everyone else had finished and it was breast meat. The staff‚Äôs response? A laugh and a casual ‚Äúchange it.‚Äù Charming.

On 12 Oct 2025, while queuing, I was skipped over in favor of the person behind me. Apparently, I was somehow invisible.
Same day, a staff member began taking my drink order, then walked off mid-sentence when someone called him. No apology, no explanation. Another staff member had to step in. Basic courtesy seems optional.

And then there‚Äôs the billing. They don‚Äôt provide itemised bills by default. The one time I requested one, it turned into a full-blown ordeal. The staff member had to manually search and key in each item, and it took 10 minutes to produce a bill. Makes you wonder how the accounting works behind the scenes, if it works at all.

I initially gave this establishment a 5 start based on my 1st visit. But I changed it today and added this review.

Amos Curry House could be a standout spot. But right now, it‚Äôs a place with excellent food and service that feels like an afterthought. A bit of training in hospitality and perhaps a functioning billing system would go a long way.

address: A-1820, Jalan Telok Cempedak, Taman Teluk Cempedak, 25050 Kuantan, Pahang, Malaysia
text:
This was my first visit, but for other members of my family, it was their 2nd or 3rd visit over the past few years.

When we arrived, there was a large group dining as part of a Christmas celebration. After being seated, we were neither greeted nor given a menu. I eventually had to go to the counter to collect the menu myself. Shortly after that, the staff noticed me and promptly served us bread.

We ordered a salad, three pasta dishes, and one salmon dish. It took about an hour for the food to arrive. Overall, the experience was just okay‚Äînothing special or memorable.

Personally, I feel that the price increase is not justified given the portion size and the ingredients in the salad and pasta. With this price, it‚Äôs better to dine in a mall or hotel for buffet.

Suggestions for Improvement:
1.	Manage Walk-Ins During Busy Times
When hosting large group dinners, consider limiting walk-in customers to prevent service delays and long wait times due to understaffing.

2.	Enhance Dining Presentation
For the price being charged, provide a more refined setup, such as tablecloths, and have the staff arrange the cutlery for customers.

3.	Address Long Wait Times Proactively
Instead of simply apologizing for the one-hour wait, take action to improve the experience. Offer drinking water, refill the bread, or provide a small sharing dessert. These gestures would leave a more positive impression on customers.

text:
I went to this shop because of its good rating .
Unfortunately quite disappointed.
We ordered sotong salted egg (squid) , kangkung  goreng and ikan pari bakar. Truth to be told the best dish was the kangkung (water spinach). We ended up not finishing the squid at all. Went with very high hopes but was a let down.

name: Wing Zone Ipoh
address: 20, Persiaran Greentown 2, Pusat Perdagangan Greentown, 30450 Ipoh, Perak, Malaysia
text:
Look, they used to be special.

Probably the only wing specialist place in Ipoh, I was a customer since the pandemic, and looked forward to their wings, burgers and wraps freshly prepared in a plethora of flavours. Although a bit pricey, the uniqueness of the menu sort of justified it.

However, since the change in management last year (see their Facebook page), I detected a significant drop in quality in almost all aspects, and they're still spiralling. The choices of flavours have reduced to less than half; the chicken wings are small, dry, tough, and not fresh; and worst of all, the flavours themselves are not tasty anymore.

Smokin' Q was the best flavour. Sweet, salty, spicy and smoky all rolled into one. But today, just the richness of the sauce remains. The sauce is curiously bland and tasted worse than your generic barbecue sauce. For "flavourholics" this is not.

The restaurant is also in a mediocre state. The air-conditioning isn't working and it's warm even in the evening. The soft drinks aren't ice-cold. Gone too are the plastic gloves to wear while eating to keep your hands clean. And I can't even choose between blue cheese or ranch anymore!

Wing Zone has become a shadow of its former self, and it's painful to see. I guess it's back to Korean chicken wings from now on.

name: Restoran Tepi Sungai
address: Jalan Sungai Manggis, Kampung Kuala Sepetang, 34650 Kuala Sepetang, Perak, Malaysia
text:
After we finished our boat trip at Port Weld, we tried to find a restaurant for seafood, and we found Port Weld Restaurant. Also known as Restoran Tepi Sungai, it was recommended by others on the internet. As it was the only seafood restaurant open for business at that time, we decided to give it a try.

The eating hall is actually located on the first floor instead of the ground floor, reachable from a flight of stairs. As we were the first customers, we got to pick the spot with the best view, overlooking the Sepetang River beneath us. Food ordering was pretty fast, and our food came quickly too.

We really liked the Blanched Cockles. They tasted fresh, and did not have the usual fishy taste that cockles have. They tasted great when mixed with minced garlic and chillies.

The Salted Egg Mantis Shrimp we ordered was not good at all. The meat was tough, dry, and it did not have the usual fragrance of salted egg. We doubted the freshness of the mantis shrimp. Overall, it was a disappointment.

We ordered the simple Steamed Crab, hoping to taste the crab without it being overwhelmed by sauces that are usually present in other cooking methods, which sometimes overpower the taste of the crabs themselves. However, the crabs were just so-so, lacking the natural sweetness of crab meat, and the dish came with one of the crabs missing one of its claws. There must be better choices for crabs elsewhere.

To complete the meal, we also ordered Stir Fried Malabar Spinach (Ê∏ÖÁÇíÂ∏ùÁöáËãó). As usual, I like my vege cooked simple, and simple is good.

Overall, only the cockles were great, and the rest of the seafood dishes were below expectations. The price was considered standard for seafood, and we think they could do better.

name: Restoran Citarasa Kampung PD
address: Citarasa Kampung PD, 1, Port Dickson By Pass, Taman Puteri, 71000 Port Dickson, Negeri Sembilan, Malaysia
text:
My recent lunch visit to Restoran Citarasa Kampung PD on May 31st, 2025, offered a mixed experience. The restaurant boasts a wide array of kampung-style dishes, including popular choices like Gulai Lemak Cili Api, Asam Pedas, Sup Panas, Ikan Bakar, Kari, and an extensive selection of ulam-ulaman. It's certainly a spot with plenty of options to choose from.

For my meal, I opted for nasi putih with Ikan Pari Bakar, hati ayam and some vegetables. Unfortunately, the Ikan Pari Bakar was noticeably "hancing" (rancid) and inedible. I informed a waiter about the issue, and to their credit, they promptly replaced it with Ikan Kembung Bakar.

While the replacement dish was acceptable, the initial unpleasant experience with the rancid fish was quite off-putting and definitely left a lasting negative impression. Overall, I personally believe the taste of the food was just okay, nothing particularly outstanding.

In terms of pricing, I found it to be on the higher side for what was offered. Additionally, there's certainly room for improvement when it comes to the cleanliness of the establishment.

All in all, it was an okay experience, but the issue with the fish definitely overshadowed any positives.

name: Pokok IOI City Mall
address: GE-201, Ground Floor, IOI City Tower TWO, Ioi Resort, 62502 Putrajaya, Wilayah Persekutuan Putrajaya, Malaysia
text:
We visited this caf√© as part of our plan to try new places instead of sticking to the usual favourites.

First impressions were good ‚Äî the space was bright and airy, and not crowded during brunch hour. Menu offerings were fairly standard caf√© fare, though prices seemed a little on the premium side.

We ordered the Big Breakfast, Farm Bake, Nasi Lemak BOMB, a few lemonades, and later added the viral tiramisu.

Big Breakfast ‚Äì Disappointing. The bread wasn‚Äôt toasted, which made it soggy under the scrambled eggs. The salad had just two cherry tomatoes within the greens, and the portion included one hash brown wedge, a chicken sausage, two thin chicken slices, and some mushrooms. It lacked substance for the price. 2/5

Nasi Lemak BOMB ‚Äì The rice was creamy with a nice pandan aroma. But the beef rendang was tough and the ayam goreng berempah was dry. Flavours didn‚Äôt come together well. 2/5

Farm Bake ‚Äì This was the biggest letdown. We were told it would take 20‚Äì30 minutes. After 30 minutes, it still wasn‚Äôt ready. Eventually, we were told there was a kitchen issue, and were offered a complimentary cheesecake as compensation. The dish finally arrived almost an hour ‚Äî essentially a shakshouka-style bake with just two lamb meatballs. Not worth the wait or price. We couldn‚Äôt even finish it. 1/5

Tiramisu ‚Äì Marketed as ‚Äúscoop all you can,‚Äù but the taste didn‚Äôt impress. The mascarpone mix felt diluted with cream and lacked that rich, punchy flavour. 2/5

Overall, this was a pretty underwhelming experience. The service was polite, but the food didn‚Äôt deliver ‚Äî especially at the price point. Hopefully others have better luck, but we likely won‚Äôt return.

name: Warung Pok Nong (celup tepung)
address: Jalan Pantai, A1693, T145, Kampung Teliput, 21030 Kuala Terengganu, Terengganu, Malaysia
text:
Warung Pok Nong (Celup Tepung) ‚Äì Total Disaster

With over 4,000 Google reviews averaging 4.3 stars, I thought this place would be a must-try. Boy, was I wrong.

The System (5/5): To be fair, the queuing system is impressive. You first queue for a number. An old chap sizes up your group and allocates a suitable table. When your number is called, you queue for drinks. Once you‚Äôve got those in hand, you queue again for food‚Äîonly when your number comes up. Sounds tedious, but it‚Äôs actually orderly.

The Food (2/5):
‚Ä¢	Fish ICT (ikan celup tepung, RM6 each): Zero seasoning. Just gutted fish dipped in flour and deep-fried. Crispy, yes. Flavor? Nonexistent.
‚Ä¢	Cuttlefish (RM17): I came expecting the glorious whole squid from Mark Wiens‚Äô YouTube video. Instead, got sad, chopped-up pieces.
‚Ä¢	Keropok Lekor (RM2 for 3 pcs): Supposedly a KT specialty. Here, it‚Äôs fried in the same bland flour batter. Forgettable.
‚Ä¢	Cuttlefish Eggs (RM8): The only saving grace. Clean, creamy, no fishy taste. Decent portion too.

The Rest:
‚Ä¢	Chili sauce: Watery and bland. Calling it a ‚Äúdip‚Äù is generous.
‚Ä¢	Environment: Hot, no AC. Located by the seaside, which sounds nice until you‚Äôre sweating while eating. View is good though.
‚Ä¢	Parking: A nightmare. Brace yourself.

Verdict: Portions are okay, prices are reasonable, seafood is fresh‚Äîbut freshness alone can‚Äôt save tasteless cooking. Service? What service? You‚Äôll likely spend 1-1.5 hours here. Try it yourself if you must, but don‚Äôt say I didn‚Äôt warn you.

name: Restoran Asia Signature
address: 20000, Jalan Sultan Zainal Abidin, 20000 Kuala Terengganu, Terengganu, Malaysia
text:
Sincere feedback from me as a chef‚Äîyour tom yum tastes bitter and lacks depth. Let me share a few tips.

The issue likely comes from how you treat the tom yum paste. It‚Äôs already been saut√©ed during production, so boiling it for too long will make it bitter.

Here‚Äôs what you can do:

‚Ä¢ Use a direct cooking method.
‚Ä¢ Don‚Äôt mix the paste into your clear fish stock from the start.
‚Ä¢ Instead, bring your stock to a boil first, then add the paste and simmer briefly.

This way, your tom yum will taste fresher and more balanced.

text:
Restaurant C.B. Wee ‚Äì Disappointing!

When I travel on business, I often rely on Google reviews. Chinese non halal pork free restaurant. With 300+ reviews averaging 4.3 stars, this place looked promising. Sadly, I was conned again.

We arrived at 11 a.m. to an empty restaurant‚Äîjust us. Staff were busy prepping in the kitchen. Ordering was simple: the friendly server hands you a menu and you write down your choices. Chice if meat and how you want it prepared. So far, so good.

The Food (or lack thereof):
‚Ä¢	Deep Fried Cuttlefish: Fresh, yes. Flavor, no. Bland and forgettable.
‚Ä¢	Ha Look Prawns: Six medium prawns, fresh but soggy. Honestly, I believe I could‚Äôve cooked them better myself.
‚Ä¢	Lemon Chicken: How anyone can butcher such a simple dish is beyond me. Starchy chicken cutlets drowned in lemon ‚Äúslime.‚Äù Disgusting.
‚Ä¢	Fried Meehoon: The worst dish I‚Äôve had in my life‚Äîperiod. Burnt, starchy, and painful to finish. I never waste food, but this one was a test of willpower. Lesson in life: not all 4.3 stars are created equal.
‚Ä¢	Seafood Fried Rice: First two bites seemed fine, then it fell apart‚Äîunevenly cooked, bland, prawns not at their freshest.

The Rest:
‚Ä¢	No AC, but parking is aplenty.
‚Ä¢	Bill for all the above + two iced Chinese teas: RM75. Reasonable price, unreasonable regret.
‚Ä¢	The server was the only saving grace‚Äîsmiling, polite, and attentive throughout. Kudos to her.

Verdict: One of the biggest letdowns of my food-hunting life. If you value your taste buds (and sanity), skip this restaurant at all costs.

name: McDonald's Semporna DT
address: Country Lease 125340490, Mile 1, Jalan Bubul, Pekan Semporna, 91308 Semporna, Sabah, Malaysia
text:
My recent visit to this location left me disturbed and concerned for public health and safety. I had placed an order on Grab, which was confirmed. When the driver canceled, I went in to pick it up directly. The manager or supervisor on duty was evasive and unhelpful. After repeatedly insisting that it was √¢‚Ç¨≈ìno longer time,√¢‚Ç¨¬ù she finally admitted√¢‚Ç¨‚Äùafter nearly 10 minutes√¢‚Ç¨‚Äùthat my food had been eaten by staff. This was shocking, especially since the cancellation had only just occurred.

I decided to let that go and order lunch instead, also requesting a large cup of ice (even offering to pay for it). The request was flatly refused without any reasonable explanation. Apparently, providing ice in a cup for a paying customer is √¢‚Ç¨≈ìimpossible.√¢‚Ç¨¬ù

What I saw next raised serious red flags: a larger female manager wearing glasses was openly eating fries from a customer√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s order and making herself a cup of coffee using company equipment. If staff can consume food and beverages meant for paying customers, yet refuse something as harmless as ice in a cup, it begs the question√¢‚Ç¨‚Äùwhat exactly happens to our orders before they reach us?

The handling of food here is questionable at best and potentially unsafe at worst. This is not simply bad customer service√¢‚Ç¨‚Äùthis is a matter of trust, hygiene, and respect for customers. I strongly urge others to reconsider before dining here. 0/100 √¢‚Ç¨‚Äù BEWARE.

text:

name: Joo Seng Cafe
address: Ground Floor, No 125 , 1 1/2 Miles, Jalan Rock, 93200 Kuching, Sarawak, Malaysia
text:
I had a disappointing experience this morning at Joo Seng Cafe, which I feel compelled to share. I went there for breakfast with friends, and unfortunately, the meal was far from enjoyable.

1. The fried noodles, kuey teow, and yellow noodles were unacceptably oily, making them completely unappetizing. It was hard to enjoy the meal when everything was drenched in so much oil.

2. The presentation was bizarre. I ordered the fried noodles, and logically, a spoon and fork should have been served with the dish. Instead, they were placed deep inside a small bowl of clear water. At first, I assumed it was hot water for hygienic purposes, but when we asked the staff, we were shocked to find out it was actually soup! This was an unprecedented and strange way of serving utensils, and while I wasn√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t expecting fine dining, it just felt odd and unprofessional. (Forgot to take photo but you guys can try and see)

3. The pan mee soup was incredibly salty, which completely spoiled my mood.

Overall, I can only describe this meal as a "cholesterol meal set" to start the day, and I sincerely hope the management takes these points into consideration for improvement. This was definitely not the standard I was expecting from such a popular kopitiam.

However, to be fair, the roti kahwin and teh tarik were worth a try and quite nice. They were the only redeeming qualities of my visit.
